<br>
Not too well, it would appear!<br>
<br>
The toll of US, and now British, dead and injured grows daily as Iraqi resistance becomes bolder, and possibly more organised, by the day.<br>
<br>
Rumours of Sadham and his sons seen driving through villages north of Baghdad may sound unlikely but the fact that they exist at all should cause concern.<br>
<br>
Sadham-at-large is likely to provide a rallying point for resistance movements, even if he is not in overall control. Already an organisation called “The Return” seems to be engaging in more organised action against US forces.<br>
<br>
The US forces in Baghdad now seem to be stuck in a rather nasty sort of “Urban-Nam” situation in that they are reasonably secure in their compounds (Firebases) but when they go out to patrol the city streets (The Jungle) they come under lethal attack from Iraqi Irregulars and Militia! They definitely don’t control the city and it seems increasingly unlikely that they ever will.<br>
<br>
As a result of recent events in the south, we Brits have gone back to wearing our helmets. The whole situation in Iraq seems to be deteriorating rather than improving.<br>
<br>
It seems that the chances of ever getting the result that we were aiming for (a western style, western friendly, democratic government) fades by the day. (In all honestly, the chances were never that good in the first place!)<br>
<br>
I really don’t know how we can extricate ourselves from this one and still save face let alone achieve our objectives. Capturing Sadham (or proving him dead) seems to me to be essential to this. In any case I certainly do not want to see our forces still occupying Iraq in 12 months time or even by Christmas. As I have said before, the longer we are there the more we look like an army of occupation there for the oil and the less we can claim that we are there to liberate the Iraqi people. Indeed I think we have already overstayed our welcome.<br>
<br>
The way things seem to be going suggests that we may have years of this stalemate followed by an evacuation of our forces reminiscent of the collapse of South Vietnam.<br>
<br>
